column4: then you need to go listen to @jbrownyoga’s new interview with karen rain
column5: who was an early devotee of pattabhi jois
column6: and whose refusal to be silent about the sexual assault she suffered under his tutelage is changing the face of ashtanga. that’s her there in the headstand at left
column7: in this 1993 @yogaworks primary series video. next to her are richard freeman and tim miller
column8: who went on to become ashtanga icons. why didn’t she? because she was so traumatized by sexual assault at the hands of her “guru” that she left her beloved practice completely
column9: a troubling abusive pattern many fellow mysore practitioners witnessed and never called out.

column1: the bottom line is that the vinyasa practice we know and love is largely a product of a serial sexual predator. gah. seriously. 🤦🏽‍♀️ so if you teach yoga history (especially to starry-eyed newbie teachers!) and leave this shit out
column2: you are lying to your students. and doing a disservice to everyone who will ever study with them.

column1: the shadow side of yoga is real. it’s not pretty and it’s not fun to talk about. but karen does a powerful job here of sharing her story
column3: and saying it like it is
column4: even when it’s uncomfortable. her voice shakes. listening
column5: i feel her vulnerability and her bravery. and i recommit to telling the truth about the often-misogynistic history of yoga
column6: even when it feels icky and uncomfortable.

column1: we owe it to our students. be brave. do the hard work. they deserve the truth. it’s more than just rainbows and unicorns. 🦄🌈

column1: 65430;instagram;2019-01-22 12:37:53;FALSE;"one of the biggest gifts i have received since i quit drinking has been waking up to the fullness of my life. a fullness i didn’t realize i was missing out on.

column2: thinking i had full vision of the life i was living. it wasn’t until i took an active part in my own evolution that i began to see where i was still playing small. you can wait for life to happen to you or you can take radical responsbility and actively engage in your own becoming.

column1: 65533;instagram;2019-01-21 23:56:29;FALSE;"we had our first argument last night. he said a lot of cruel things that really hurt me. i know he was sorry and didn't mean the things he said. because i got flowers today.
i got flowers today. it wasn't our anniversary or any other special day. last night
column2: he threw me into a wall and started to choke me. it seemed like a nightmare. i couldn't believe it was real. i woke up this morning sore and bruised all over. i know he must be sorry because he sent me flowers today.

column1: i got flowers today. it wasn't mother's day or any other special day. last night
column2: he beat me up again. and it was much worse than all other times. if i leave him
column3: what will i do? how will i take care of my kids? what about money? i'm afraid of him and scared to leave. but i know he must be sorry because he sent me flowers today.

column1: i got flowers today. today was a very special day. it was the day of my funeral. last night he finally killed me. he beat me to death.  if only i had gathered enough courage and strength to leave him
column2: i would not have gotten flowers today.

column1: this poem is dedicated to all the victims and survivors of domestic violence.
🤞🏻the link to my story is in my bio 🤞🏻

column1: 65540;instagram;2019-01-22 09:38:59;FALSE;"sex abuse scandal hits south korea's elite skating scene

the prized elite world of south korean speed skating has been mired in scandal following a wave of allegations from female skaters who say that they were were sexually abused by their coaches and that it was covered up.
for a country that is a world leader in speed skating
column3: this is a serious development. other sporting federations say they are also now investigating claims of inappropriate behaviour.

column1: many see this as south korea's #metoo movement finally being taken seriously
column2: even if only through the prism of elite sport.
five unnamed female skaters have come forward accusing their coaches of abuse. one skater alleged that a coach forcibly kissed her and then verbally abused her when she rejected his advances.
represented by a group called solidarity for young skaters (sys)
column3: made their allegations public in a news conference held at south korea's parliament on monday alongside a south korean lawmaker sohn hye-won who has also taken up this cause.

column1: the group said the women chose to remain anonymous because they fear retaliation from those who support their coaches and the wider skating community. ""they are very much afraid of potential retaliation and possible rejection from the community
column3: a lawyer for solidarity for young skaters

column1: ms sohn and the pressure group also called for an investigation into jun myung-kyu
column2: the former national team coach and a hugely influential figure in south korean speed skating
column3: who they accused of concealing misconduct.

column1: mr park said mr jun's actions had gone undetected for years because he had ""influence over the korean ice skating community... because [the] community and some politicians have protected him."" mr jun has denied having any prior knowledge of the allegations or that he had knowledge of the abuse that led to one of his coaches being jailed for assault.

column2: but you survived it.;;en;;;;;;0;;pierrelamarj;Pierre LaMar Johnson;;0;False;4;0;0;98;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/7dbb7275630d5df1f94790be69fd311a/5D17F510/t51.2885-15/e35/49651348_145328316463304_885045905380226249_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;it was traumatic
column3: but you survived it.;it was traumatic

column2: but not completely yet .. it's 4:41 am ...

column1: this dream is recurrent where my grandfather is hitting me
column2: punishing strongly or simply sexually abusing me
column4: sometimes one of my uncles ... every scar on my legs and in my soul
column5: reminds me of the most cruel moments of my life .. the biggest scar i have on my leg is the one that appears in this video. my grandfather opened my skin with a heavy blow with the heavy buckle of his belt
column6: they did not take me to the hospital for fear that i would report him and the wound was open for weeks
column7: only my grandmother made me cures with home remedies
column8: until that my wound began to heal .. honestly i still have a hard time talking about this openly because i'm ashamed
column10: i feel guilty for not asking for help in time
column11: but i was just a girl and for years i knew no other world than that: my environment was full of physical
column13: mental and emotional abuse ... something inside of me knew that all that was not right but it got to the point where my mind got used to it .. i did not know a family environment of love
column14: so i assumed since childhood what that was life ...

column1: i always looked for places to hide
column2: but when i heard my grandfather shout my name
column3: i had to leave where he found me or beat me to death ... many times just hearing him say my name made me pee ... it took me a lot of work to overcome it and time later because of that ""problem"" and because of my scars and my orthopedic shoes: i was the victim of bullying throughout the primary

column1: we all have scars: some of us have scars on the skin
column3: or in the heart .. but we all have scars ..

column1: and if i could overcome all this

column1: this piece is my small contribution to ‘the women of troy’ project supporting the production put on by eagles nest theatre company. the initiative is to combat violence against women through creativity and collaboration.
we speak of violence against women
column2: yet when we turn to our sisters we are largely oblivious that 1 in 5 of them have experienced sexual violence since the age of 15. more so
column3: 1 in 3 have experienced physical violence and the chances were that this was in their home; a place of safety and refuge. “violence against women was endemic to warlike society 2500 years ago. the threat of war is no longer prevalent for most first world citizens
column4: but the level to which women across the globe are subjected to violence in their private and personal spaces is nothing short of an epidemic” (eagles nest theatre co.). have we not evolved beyond this?

column1: it shakes the skeletons of my mother’s mothers to think that their trauma has brought no change.
it leaches into the spirits of our boys brought into this world through wombs whose memories tell dark stories.
it tarnishes our future when these boys perpetually continue the cycle of all they’ve glimpsed through dungeons behind dull eyes.
it leaves rusty red stains when women hold the hands of the perpetrators
column3: and stand idle with clenched sledgehammer jaws.

column1: let’s tell our stories and hold hands while the elders sing songs of healing.
maybe the songs will carry into the valleys and over the hills and far away.
maybe the songs will spread far and wide;
and maybe they will go down in history and be sung in another 250 years time when things are better. maybe things will be better.
this collaboration is still in full swing;

column1: 65762;instagram;2019-01-22 04:15:10;FALSE;""" कम्युनिस्ट कनक सरकार को कड़ी से कड़ी सजा मिले।"" जादवपुर यूनिवर्सिटी
column2: कोलकाता में अंतर्राष्ट्रीय संबंध पढ़ाने वाले कम्युनिस्ट प्रोफेसर कनक सरकार ने रविवार को एक फेसबुक पोस्ट में स्त्रियों का अपमान करते हुए एक कुवाँरी लड़की की तुलना 'सीलबंद बोतल' या 'सीलबंद पैकेट' से की थी। बाद में उन्होंने पोस्ट को डर के कारण हटा और भाषण की स्वतंत्रता का दावा करने वाली दूसरी पोस्ट में कार्यवाही को सही ठहराया। पिछले दो दशकों से अध्यापन कार्य कर रहे कनक सरकार ने अपने फेसबुक पर लिखा था - "" बहुत सारे लड़के बेवकूफ बने हुए हैं। वो बीबी के रूप में एक वर्जिन लड़की को लेकर जागरूक नहीँ हैं। वर्जिन लड़की एक सीलबंद बोतल या सीलबंद पैकेट की तरह है। क्या तुम सील टूटी कोल्डड्रिंक की बोतल या सील खुले बिस्किट के पैकेट को खरीदना पसंद करोगे? इसी तरह तुम्हारी बीबी का केस है।"" ""हम भारत सरकार और देश की आमजनता से माँग करते हैं कि कम्युनिस्ट कनक सरकार जैसे अपराधी को कड़ी से कड़ी ऐसी सजा दी जाए ताकि वो दुबारा कुछ भी गलत बोलने और करने लायक ही न बचे। और इसके साथी कम्युनिस्टों को भी करारा जवाब दिया जाए। चाहे कोई भी अपराधी हो
column3: उसे बिल्कुल भी रियायत न देकर कड़ी से कड़ी सजा सुनायी जाए तभी हमारा भारत देश पुनः विश्वगुरु बन पाएगा और सभ्य समाज का निर्माण कर सकेगा।"" कम्युनिस्ट गिरोह के सन्दर्भ में मेरी ""एकता"" नामक कविता प्रासंगिक है -

column1: ;`` कम्युनिस्ट कनक सरकार को कड़ी से कड़ी सजा मिले। '' जादवपुर यूनिवर्सिटी , कोलकाता में अंतर्राष्ट्रीय संबंध पढ़ाने वाले कम्युनिस्ट प्रोफेसर कनक सरकार ने रविवार को एक फेसबुक पोस्ट में स्त्रियों का अपमान करते हुए एक कुवाँरी लड़की की तुलना 'सीलबंद बोतल ' या 'सीलबंद पैकेट ' से की थी। बाद में उन्होंने पोस्ट को डर के कारण हटा और भाषण की स्वतंत्रता का दावा करने वाली दूसरी पोस्ट में कार्यवाही को सही ठहराया। पिछले दो दशकों से अध्यापन कार्य कर रहे कनक सरकार ने अपने फेसबुक पर लिखा था - `` बहुत सारे लड़के बेवकूफ बने हुए हैं। वो बीबी के रूप में एक वर्जिन लड़की को लेकर जागरूक नहीँ हैं। वर्जिन लड़की एक सीलबंद बोतल या सीलबंद पैकेट की तरह है। क्या तुम सील टूटी कोल्डड्रिंक की बोतल या सील खुले बिस्किट के पैकेट को खरीदना पसंद करोगे ? इसी तरह तुम्हारी बीबी का केस है। '' `` हम भारत सरकार और देश की आमजनता से माँग करते हैं कि कम्युनिस्ट कनक सरकार जैसे अपराधी को कड़ी से कड़ी ऐसी सजा दी जाए ताकि वो दुबारा कुछ भी गलत बोलने और करने लायक ही न बचे। और इसके साथी कम्युनिस्टों को भी करारा जवाब दिया जाए। चाहे कोई भी अपराधी हो , उसे बिल्कुल भी रियायत न देकर कड़ी से कड़ी सजा सुनायी जाए तभी हमारा भारत देश पुनः विश्वगुरु बन पाएगा और सभ्य समाज का निर्माण कर सकेगा। '' कम्युनिस्ट गिरोह के सन्दर्भ में मेरी `` एकता '' नामक कविता प्रासंगिक है - तुम भी दूसरों पर हँसना छोड़ो। वो भी छोड़ देंगे। वो भीड़ नहीँ , एकता है। समाज की समाज के विकास के लिए एकता है। देश की देश के विकास के लिए एकता है। वो भीड़ नहीँ , भारतीय संस्कृति के अनुयायियों की एकता है। देश का विचार देश के लिए , देशवासियों की एकता है। विदेशी विचार नहीँ चलेगा , नहीँ चलेगा। देश का विचार ही चलेगा , भारतीय विचार ही चलेगा।। ।। जय भारतीय संस्कृति।। ।। जय भारत माता।। ।। जय श्रीराम।। ✍ कुशराज _22/1/19_7:06am etoo ushraaz rc u rantikari astravadi ationlalist haratsarkar ndiangovernment odisarkar ndianculture ndiancivilization ndiansociety abhyasamaj arksist ommunist arxist omrade anaksarkar adavpurunivesity olkata iveditamenon nu elhi eyasarkar ;[('``'

column1: be wary of any company that capitalizes on a social movement. this is a trend in advertising that's extremely effective at creating emotional connections
column2: and is only more reason to look at it with a critical eye. this social justice  advertising seldom leads to drastic change - if anything
column3: it usually hinders it. if you investigate what companies do when they align with social movements
column4: they all follow the same formula:

column1: 1. donate as little as is required by law
2. set up a website with specific messaging

column2: these commercials control the narrative around social issues
column3: and it can negate any real change in law or society  since consumers assume that companies have our interests in mind so we don't have to worry. we've seen it before with doves beauty campaign
column6: bell lets talk.... ugh. and these are just a few examples!

column2: we can argue it is better to encourage these conversations
column3: but gillette didn't start the #metoo movement.  individuals like you and me started it
column4: not a razor company. don't let them take that power from you - it is your debates amongst your peers and on your keyboards that gave it this momentum. gillette  only scratched the surface rather than delving into a deep
column5: intersectional issue with toxic masculinity dating back to the victorian era.

column2: marketers now realize that women often make consumer choices for men (ie pick their deodorant/razors/shampoo/etc). so to me
column3: it only makes sense that this gillette commercial would target the #metoo movement. but as you can see from this ad
column4: they don't have a particularly feminist track record.

column1: 65797;instagram;2019-01-22 03:24:52;FALSE;"“we can never take anyone any further than we have been willing to go ourselves.” -dan allender

this is not a quote from mlk.  and when i considered my participation on this platform today i wanted to speak to those of us who are privileged and wish to engage as allies and friends.  we must consider the impact and extent of our inner work.  if you have not known where you were oppressed or powerless or abused or isolated or rejected or silenced within your own story
column2: you will be severely limited in your capacity to be present in this divided climate.  it will unknowingly halt and exhaust you
column4: you’ll bring pity and unneeded things because you have not taken the time to understand the hidden offering in your own story.

column1: i do not think it is a coincidence that geographical and physical refugees are being persecuted and abused at the same time the american church is isolating and rejecting an entire generation of followers.  i do not think it is a coincidence that #metoo
column4: and nathan phillips are shining such bright light into a country of fear filled hatred.  to reframe the quote above
column5: you can only hate others as much as you have hated yourself.  you can only reject others as much as you have rejected yourself.  and let me be clear
column6: this is not a cry for compassion on the perpetrators

column1: 65837;instagram;2019-01-22 02:58:10;FALSE;"let's talk about the healing and #recovery journey. ⁣
after you're aware- really after you allow  yourself to stop resisting the flashbacks and memories (no matter how long ago it was) the next step is to accept what has happened. ⁣
how do you accept what happened?  how do you allow yourself to be okay that it took place?  that's so hard because you didn't ask for it
column4: so is accepting it condoning it?⁣

column1: those are all great questions.  i want to tell you how you can accept what's happened to you in regards to #sexualtrauma. ⁣
1- remember your recovery path is for you not other people or the abuser. ⁣
2- keep in mind the feelings you want to feel when you're healed.  example- freedom
3-allow yourself to feel the emotions of the events.  example-sad
column4: repressing the emotions will only make it worse.  it's okay to have any emotions that you have regardless.  so keep in mind this is just as the same. this will help you allow yourself to be okay with accepting the abuse more and more.⁣

column1: 4- find a way to express your emotions
column2: the flashbacks and memories in a safe place.  that might mean journaling
column4: etc.  do what you think is best for you. everyone is different. keep in mind positive ways.  escaping will not help this at all.  as i've learned

column1: 5- find a support group or even a person.  it's vital to your recovery to have people in your corner that know what's going on. they can be there for you when times are really rough.  it also helps you accept it more when your speak about what happened.  you take away the power the event owns and gives the power back to you. ⁣
acceptance is possible.  it doesn't mean you're happy about what happened.  it means you're on the path of recovery and changing your life
column2: and finding your power again.  remember this is not for the other person.  this is for you. ⁣

column1: 65891;instagram;2019-01-22 02:40:42;FALSE;"i worry some days i won't wake up ... that i won't feel my dogs as they lay gently against me; that i won't feel the warmth of the sun on my back again
column2: or the gentle cool morning breeze ...

column3: emotional or mental fear. the fear is very physical ... and it's very real.

column1: up until recently the fear that's controlled my life has been a #metoo thing ... it's been with me since i was 6 years old.

column3: i've been working with an amazing jiu jitsu teacher and an incredible counselor. their time
column4: compassion and expertise is helping to strengthen me physically and mentally
column5: so that fear no longer control me.

column1: but yesterday i came to realise there's a new fear in town ... one that lurks and keeps me restless at night. and it's something i have almost no control over.
i didn't realize how big an effect it's having on me ... almost every moment of the day ... and it can leave me literally gasping for air.
it's called chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (copd). usually it's associated with emphysema. but for many of us with sjögrens syndrome it becomes an accepted way of life.
the daily (and often exhausting) battle against being almost suffocated by our own mucus can wear you down
column2: frey the edges of your very being
column3: and cause severe distress ... fearing for our very lives.

column1: yesterday was a bad day ... breathing was tough and i was exhausted. but i had two choices: retreat and wallow; or stand and fight.
and so all i can ask for is the strength and courage to continue the good fight.

it is called chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (copd). usually it is associated with emphysema. but for many of us with sjögrens syndrome it becomes an accepted way of life.
the daily (and often exhausting) battle against being almost suffocated by our own mucus can wear you down
column2: frey the edges of your very being
column3: and cause severe distress ... fearing for our very lives.

column1: yesterday was a bad day ... breathing was tough and i was exhausted. but i had two choices: retreat and wallow; or stand and fight.
and so all i can ask for is the strength and courage to continue the good fight.

column1: 65901;instagram;2019-01-22 02:45:03;FALSE;i would have run away from these words in my times of deepest suffering. but i now i can look at the redemption all around me and see that the price tag of my pain cannot compare to the “glory that is coming” and the redemption that my heart and spirit and body dance in every day. i’m living in the fulfillment of the promises of god. and i can promise you this - the deeper and longer the pain
column2: the sweeter the redemption. we throw around the phrase “don’t throw your pearls before the swine” from the bible quite often
column4: i see that as grossly misused. pearls are formed through severe irritation in a creature. a most priceless and sought after item
column5: a pearl is not the product of a happy life in which all goes just as hoped...it is a product of a suffering creature buried in the darkness so deep that only some dare to explore. but for those of us who have been hurtled into these depths
column6: the redemption promised in this life is so sweet and so sure. it doesn’t matter if if you caused your own suffering or if someone else caused your pain- redemption is still your promise

column1: 65927;instagram;2019-01-22 01:55:42;FALSE;"“i have this life because i put in the work when everyone else was tired"". words from #travelblogger @veerabianca - who is living a blogger’s life full of #rich adventures. but “success” does not come easy. she kindly gave us permission to reproduce her post. thank you veera for being real ❤️ “when most people see the glory.  the incredible adventures around the world. champagne on red carpet.  the opportunities that knock on the door.
most forget it's not a matter of luck
column2: but of extremely hard work and sacrifices.  i've worked hard on this dream for as long as i can remember.  i've stayed up endless nights to edit photos (like last night)
column3: finish presentations or to update my blog.  i've missed out on time with friends and family - more than anyone should.  i've missed birthdays and weddings.

i worked at the airport and had to get up ‪at 2am‬ on weekends to walk 2 miles to the bus stop in -25c weather just to get to work for the morning flights.  it was inconvenient - but i had my mind set on it.

column1: i've cried on the bathroom floor wanting to quit and feeling like i cannot handle it.  i've been told i suck.  i've been scared
column2: pushed to the side and used - in all the ways a woman can be used.

column1: i've taken on opportunities when i've had zero idea how to do something.  but that to me is the only way to learn.

so as another monday comes knocking on the door. let this be a reminder that behind any successful person you may admire is a ridiculous amount of work and sacrifices.  it's not anything you can't have
column2: but consider carefully how much of yourself you are really ready to invest in a dream.  and if the answer is everything - go make this monday your b*tch.” #freespirit #explorer #adventurers #traveladdict #travelphoto";;en;#travelblogger

column1: the 30-year-old english poet from indian origin and graphic designer by profession has started writing from the age of 12. after being rejected by 137 traditional publishers
column2: she gained worldwide fame by posting her work on instagram and tumblr. . .

column1: this fierce feminist writes powerful poems and short stories about abuse
column5: and the role of women in society. nikita gill has also supported the recent ‘#metoo' movement against sexual abuse. she portrays the nature of love
column6: and how to become whole again after being broken

column1: 65965;instagram;2019-01-22 01:13:00;FALSE;"have you ever got in a car on a cold morning? your back hits the seat and you immediately bounce and shiver because the seat feels ice cold?
what happens when you stay there for a few minutes?
does your body heat help the seat become more survivable? after a while you hardly even notice the cold anymore.

your presence there is what transforms something cold to something warm.. we all have some people in our life who don't see eye to eye with us yet we still love them. sometimes just being there and reassuring them can help them warm up to you. your loving presence might sometimes be what's needed to help then see things from your point of view.
i know it doesn't always work and  i know love will never change someone who doesn't respect you
but if you mutually respect each other then you can both evolve.
our growth comes from the struggles we face within us but we also need a warm presence to help keep us growing.
love people and be that warm sun light they need to help them grow

column2: it’s me! i really didn’t have an introduction of any sorts planned but brian took this photo of me yesterday and i don’t hate it so i thought i’d say hello. 👋🏼 i usually use these selfie posts to talk about something that’s been on my mind so here we go:

column1: something that really drives me crazy is seeing women shaming other women. truthfully
column2: women get shamed and objectified by men all the damn time but it sure is rough in girl world & unfortunately i see this all the time in the photography world especially. women making comments about the way another woman in a photograph has chosen to dress/do her makeup/wear her hair/change her body with plastic surgery/etc and ladies let me just say we have got to do better than that. i believe very strongly in equality for all and i love being a woman despite the fact that my gender intrinsically comes with some inequalities. i empathize strongly with the #metoo movement and i am a very loud voice for change and bringing to light the injustices that women face every single day but here’s the thing: change has to start with us. if we can’t respect one another
column3: how will anyone else respect us?

column1: i find these comments are often a window into someone’s own insecurities and trust me i am not perfect myself. i have a boat load of insecurities and i suffer from jealousy just like most of my fellow humans. but social media only makes this all exponentially worse because it’s so easy to hide behind a computer screen pick apart a strangers appearance without ever having to face the person you’re judging. regardless
column2: you always have a choice on how to act or react to something and kindness is always an option. my life motto is “do no harm
column3: but take no sh!t” so stand up for yourself and stand up for your fellow woman. we’re all in this together
